So we agree that there was a period of decline, we agree there was a migration period, we agree population centers became a clusterfuck, literature was lost, but we disagree that there was a period colloquially known as "the dark age". Dude, I fucked your mom. Just because you change the name of something doesn't make it a different thing.

As for quality of life, historians typically measure that by estimating the access a commoner would have to certain resources. Nutrition and diet can be known from records, as well as samples taken from bones. (There's actually a neat study about how the diet of an average roman citizen was almost identical to the diet of a modern man. It's pretty neat you should check it out.). Yes, I understand that there wasn't some sort of apocalyptic day of terror where mankind fell into a thousand years of darkness, but it's indisputable that there was a period where technology became much less available and regressed in some areas, and people were generally poorer.
